Excellent "starter" soup for fall menus -- an enthusiastic four forks. As another poster said, addition of the chutney makes this recipe rate four forks, without it the soup is still a solid three. I roasted the squash first which made it easier to peel and added a mellow taste. I did strain the soup and found a few strings I guess I missed earlier. TIP: to make the squash easier to cut into chunks, cook for a minute or two in the microwave.

Rating: 4
Wonderful soup. It's not a hearty, applesauce-consistency soup (like most butternut swuash soups). Rather, it's smooth, fruity, spicy, and fairly light. For those not in the know (like me), coriander is the same thing as cilantro. Also, I used 2 Fresno chilis instead of jalapenos. And, like others, I didn't strain it. Trust me, don't bother. Even without the chutney, it's a great soup, but with the chutney, the soup goes from 3 forks to 4. It could be served in the finest restaurants (and I wish it would). We're serving it for a Thanksgiving first-course.

